<font color="#FF0000"> FURIOUS CONNIPTIONS OVER POST</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 17 12:49:51 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Sorry Gerald, <br>
To write about how others supportive of the war is not what I can write about. That remains foreign to me. <br>
I never meant to dishonor anyone that served in Nam. If you feel guilty about that sorry, what I have written is not meant to discredit any vet. If you feel guilty about not having seen what I saw, sorry.<br>
I choose Marine Corps Green because I knew I was going to Nam, figured I would get good training and I did. Did it help me stay alive, sort of? <br>
The best advised I received was from an old salt going home.<br>
He was a Lance Corporal wearing a wrinkled old khaki uniform. His hat cover was missing its Marine Corps eagle and anchor emblem, and his shoes were old, unpolished and missing their shoelaces. As an officer, you probably would have gotten all over his case.<br>
&quot;Keep yah ass down, keep yah mouth shut, lissen to the old timers, don't volunteer for nuthin; an' in thirteen months you'll leave here in one piece,&quot; he said with a southern drawl, as he handed me the funny looking money along with about 15 South Vietnamese paper dollars in various denominations. <br>
&quot;Ahm on mah way home, an' I ain't got no time ta change this,&quot; he said, as he turned around and walked agilely away.  He had a slight limp and this added to the admiration he was receiving from us, new boots.  I last caught a glimpse of him as he turned the corner and walked toward the out going flights barrack. <br>
&quot;He made it through Nam, and is now homeward bound, I can make it too,&quot; I said to myself.<br><br>
It was not until I started to do my research about a year ago, that I found out others did not fight the same type of war we fought. That others were given medals, stars, and colorful ribbons for what we often did in combat without any recognition. That's the reason I never got the medals I had been put up for. In the Corps they were issued out in quotas and by the time they came down to the guy in the field most of them had already been spoken for. Most officers got a Silver Star for just having served in a combat situation, oh! It was written up real nice, but most of them will tell you today, after seeing what their troops went through that they did not deserve the medals.<br>
And if I needed any parts for my weapons, I knew I would never get them through proper channels, so I traded what we captured in the field (communist made weapons, etc.) for ammo pouches, extra canteens, cleaning gear, camouflaged utilities. A whole batch of us were send back to our units from the Army's hospital in Chu Lai when we found out where they kept camouflaged shorts and sort of helped ourselves to a pair.  Camouflaged Shorts, can you believe that?  Who ever was in charge of that base sure was upset when we broke into his storage shed. <br><br>
Lurp packages. Hey that was a good one. When we got a hold of ONE of those packages, felt like we were eating at a fine French restaurant.  Sorry Gerald your war was not mine. At the reunion I found out what ribbons I had not received and added another row. Why? They don't mean anything; I was caught up with emotional high and pride everyone else was feeling. I enjoy the Combat Action Ribbon and my 96' LA Riots ribbon just fine.  Soon they will go into a shadow box, but the Marine Corps ribbon keeps me pounding away at the book as do the pictures and maps others have send me. <br>
Hey, maybe after this book I'll write one on LAPD, Nope! I threw away from Whambaugh has written about, wasn't sensational enough.<br><br>

<p><code>-- The ultimate macho super patriotic Marine   (Cook Barela, USMC) </code><p>


